    <div id="mma2" class="step sec4" data-x="3540" data-y="-110" data-scale=".1">
	<h2>Markov Monoid algorithm</h2>

	<br/>
	The Markov Monoid is a <i>stabilisation monoid</i>:
	<ul>
		<li>binary composition</li>
		<li>stabilisation, denoted $\sharp$ (<b>intuition</b>: $u^\sharp = \lim_n u^n$)</li>
	</ul>
	It satisfies some natural axioms:
	$$u \cdot (v \cdot u)^\sharp = (u \cdot v)^\sharp \cdot u$$

<!--
	$$\begin{array}{c}
		(u^\sharp)^\sharp = u^\sharp \\
		u \cdot (v \cdot u)^\sharp = (u \cdot v)^\sharp \cdot u
	\end{array}$$
-->	
	<div class="slide_step">
	If there exists an element $M$ such that
		$$\forall t \in Q, M(s_0, t) = 1 \implies t \in F$$
	then the Markov Monoid algorithm answers "$\mathcal{A}$ has value 1", otherwise "$\mathcal{A}$ does not have value 1".
	</div>
    </div>

    <!-- end of section 4 -->
    </div>

